passages.text: China (PRC) | Healthcare Services Gushengtang

GST reported \(10\%\) yoy revenue growth in 1H25, and cut FY25 rev guidance further, to \(10 - 15\%\) . We think the \(20\%\) FY26 rev guidance is likely to miss on: 1) slowdown of mature stores; 2) B/S constraints pose challenges in supporting sizable M&A at favorable valuations; 3) intensifying competition from long- standing TCM leaders, such as Tong Ren Tang. Meanwhile, VBP on decoctions could pressure profitability further. Maintain UNPF.

1H25 miss, guidance cut further - GST's organic revenue growth slowed to \(8\%\) in 1H25, (vs \(28\%\) in 2024). Mgmt has further reduced FY25 revenue guidance to \(10 - 15\%\) yoy (lowered to \(+25\%\) from \(+30\%\) in April) while maintaining a \(\sim 30\%\) yoy profit target for FY25. Although mgmt guided \(\sim 20\%\) revenue growth in FY26 on external expansion through sizable M&As, we think it is likely to miss again on: 1) growth slowdown of mature stores; 2) balance sheet constraints ( \(\sim\) RMB1bn cash on hand) pose challenges in supporting sizable M&As at favorable valuations; 3) intensifying competition from long- standing TCM leaders such as Tong Ren Tang Clinics.

We don't believe Al+TCM is the solution for GST - Given the nature of TCM treatment, we believe patients visit TCM clinics primarily for the expertise of TCM masters, who are scarce. Though GST has explored online consultations and Al + TCM tools to simulate the masters' experience and serve more clients, we believe this approach is unconvincing to patients, as the essence of TCM lies in bespoke treatments based on in- person consultations.

VBP on decoctions to pressure profitability - TCM decoction GPO has become one of the NHSA's priorities in 2025. Seventy percent of GST's profit is from regular decoctions; VBP would dilute its centralized supply- chain edge and pressure profitability. GST has been improving product mix with more TCM paste and in- hospital preparations to ease margin pressure, but transitioning to these alternatives will take time as GST needs to streamline the manufacturing supply chain or explore partnerships to scale up in- house preparations.

1H25 Results Recap - 1H25 revenue of Rmb1.5bn \((+10\%\) yoy), driven by a \(15\%\) yoy growth in customer volume, offset by a \(5\%\) yoy decline in the ASP. Mgmt remains confident in overseas expansion, with SG sales increased to Rmb2mn in 1H25 from Rmb1mn in 1H24. GPM increased to \(30.6\%\) in 1H25 from \(29.4\%\) in 1H24, benefiting from a \(7\%\) yoy reduction in rent cost (adding \(1\%\) to GPM, on our estimates) and operating expense savings. SG&A ratio declined to \(18.2\%\) in 1H25 vs \(19.8\%\) in 1H24. Net profit grew to Rmb152mn \((+42\%\) yoy), or \(+15\%\) if excluding one- offs.
Implications - We revise revenue lower to factor in lower- than- expected organic growth, and adjust net profit from the cost saving in SG&A. Maintain UNPF, with PT unchanged at HK\$26.0.
Please see analyst certifications, important disclosure information, and information regarding the status of non-US analysts on pages 4-9 of this report. \\* Jefferies Hong Kong Limited

We rate at Gushengtang UNPF given: 1) uncertainty about expansion into lower- tier cities with weaker out- of- pocket purchasing power and local clinic competition; 2) margin pressure from GPO on TCM decoctions, disrupting GST's core advantage in supply chain mgmt, with \(70\%\) of profit potentially affected; 3) stricter reimbursement policy on TCM clinics due to budgeting pressure.
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View
Steady growth in market size of TCM healthcare services.
Steady clinic network expansion.
Stricter reimbursement policy on TCM clinics due to budgeting pressure.
PT of HK\$26 based on DCF valuation.

Stronger- than- expected growth in TCM healthcare services market size. Faster- than- expected clinic network expansion. Faster- than- expected market share gain. Faster- than- expected margin expansion. Upside PT of HK\$39 based on DCF valuation.

Weaker- than- expected market size growth for TCM healthcare services. Slower- than- expected clinic network expansion. Shrinking market share due to competition. Worse- than- expected margin pressure. Downside PT of HK\$18 based on DCF valuation.

Top Material Issues: 1) Social responsibility, 2) Protecting the rights of shareholders, 3) Protecting the rights of clients, 4) Protecting the rights of suppliers, 5) Protecting the rights of employees, 6) Public relations, 7) Ensuring product quality and safety, 8) Environmental protection and sustainable development, 9) Adhering to business ethics.
1) Greenhouse gas emphasized: achieve annual carbon emission growth not exceeding \(5\%\) in the context of expected growth of \(10\%\) in the production plan in 2023
2) Exhaust gas: continuously reduce exhaust gas emissions.
3) Solid waste: generate no more than 8kg of hazardous and non-hazardous solid waste per month in each clinic
4) Energy management: reduce energy consumption per unit income on a continuous basis
5) Water resources: improve the utilization efficiency of water resources and reduce the water resource consumption per unit income year by year

1) What are the projected investments and potential savings in achieving the established ESG targets? 
2) What is the strategy for talent retention and development to improve human capital?

- Slower revenue growth and lower revenue per store - 2025- Lower profit margin amid policy headwinds and slower earnings growth - 2025- Stricter reimbursement policy on TCM clinics - 2025- Expanded scope and larger-than-expected price cuts from further rounds of TCM decoction GPOs - 2025

Gushengtang is a top- ten private TCM healthcare service provider in China (with \(0.6\%\) market share in 2020), and the third- largest TCM services chain in China in terms of number of institutions (i.e. number of hospitals and clinics) per company estimates. It is the first and only TCM service provider listed on the Hong Kong and China stock markets.

Our HK\$26.0 price target for Gushengtang is derived from DCF methodology, which factors in our revenue and earnings forecasts up to 2034E, with WACC of \(10.6\%\) and terminal growth rate of \(2.0\%\) . Risks: 1) regulatory risks in TCM services, 2) competition, 3) talent retention risk, 4) uncertainty on partnerships, 5) hospital network expansion risk, 6) medical disputes and legal issues.
